First: the nutrition. Information on his dietary habits is non-existent but by the fact that even in his late years he was quite thin while standing at the height of 5'1 we can easily deduce he was not a fan of bulking. To imitate his diet you should eat at maintenance but cut...

Man of power: Yukio Mishima. Writer. Japanese. Purged his weakness through sun and steel. 

Finding information about his gym habits was rough!

Training routine, exercises and nutrition - a thread:

His gym routine consisted of three weekly workouts. On the English part of the internet there is sadly zero information of his exercises, so I had to go, armed with Google Translate, into the depths of the Japanosphere.

junk and high carb foods, focusing instead of meals high in protein (even though low in caloric content)

His "cardio" consisted of training karate, boxing and kendo. At one point he also tried swimming but failed miserably, being described as "sinking like a rock" in the pool.

He disliked the regular bench press. For his chest, he focused on the LOWER PECS and his favourite exercise was the DECLINE DUMBBELL PRESS. His lower pecs were the bread and butter of his physique: they gave him his iconic physique and are the focus of most of his photos.

Legs. I read that Mishima did squats but I'm not inclined to believe it: his legs were the least developed part of his physique. It is known that when he modeled for photographers, he always insisted pictures be taken from a specific angle to hide his small legs (n show low pecs)

For abdominals his favourite exercise (and his favourite move in the gym overall!) was the LEANING TOWER OF PISA. It consisted of him lying on a bench, holding to it with his hands - and then raising his legs and his entire torso with them: basically a dragon flag!

>pic related

They were the only part of his body he was insecure about. Even if he did squats, he probably used very high repetitions and very low weights. If you want to have Mishima's body: focusing on the upper body is the way to go.

Even though Mishima's routine and diet are nothing spectacular, his focus on lower pecs, abs and biceps makes for an interesting training and physique - and his books and essays are some of the most inspiring stuff for every weightlifter! This was Yukio Mishima, man of power.

He did the "Leaning tower of Pisa" for sets of ten repetitions.

It is written that he also enjoyed doing lots of push-ups and isometric work. Sometimes he also did bench press, but as I said above he disliked it and mostly sticked to decline dumbbell work.
